# Angular Services and Dependency Injection

A **service** is a class that holds shared logic or data — API calls, state, utilities — separated from components. **Dependency Injection (DI)** is Angular's mechanism for automatically creating and providing those services wherever they're needed.

Think of DI as a **vending machine in a building**. Instead of every employee making their own coffee machine (constructors that `new` dependencies), they walk to the vending machine (the injector) and get an instance. The building (Angular) manages the inventory.

```
Without DI (tightly coupled, hard to test):
  class DataComponent {
    private service = new UserService();  // tightly coupled
  }

With DI (loosely coupled, testable):
  class DataComponent {
    constructor(private userService: UserService) {}  // injected
  }
  // Angular creates UserService and provides it — you don't manage instances
```

## Creating a Service

```typescript
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { HttpClient } from '@angular/common/http';
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'  // singleton across the whole app
})
export class UserService {
  private readonly API = '/api/users';

  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}  // injected into the service!

  getUsers(): Observable<User[]> {
    return this.http.get<User[]>(this.API);
  }

  getUserById(id: string): Observable<User> {
    return this.http.get<User>(`${this.API}/${id}`);
  }
}
```

## providedIn — Where Is the Service Singleton Created?

```
providedIn: 'root'
  ├── ONE instance for the entire application
  ├── Tree-shakeable (if never injected, not bundled)
  └── Most common choice — use this by default

providedIn: 'platform'
  └── Shared across multiple Angular apps on the same page (rare)

providedIn: 'any'
  └── Unique instance per lazy-loaded module (deprecated)

No providedIn — in providers: [] array:
  ├── Module-level: providers: [UserService] in NgModule
  │     └── ONE instance per module and its children
  └── Component-level: providers: [UserService] in @Component
        └── NEW instance per component instance (and its children)
```

## The Injector Hierarchy

Angular has a **tree of injectors** matching the component tree:

```
Root Injector (providedIn: 'root')
  │
  ├── Module Injector (providers: [] in NgModule)
  │     │
  │     └── Component Injector (providers: [] in @Component)
  │           │
  │           └── Child Component Injector
  │
  └── Environment Injectors (lazy-loaded routes)

Resolution order: Angular walks UP the tree from the requesting
component until it finds the service.

     ComponentC needs UserService
          │
          ↑ not in ComponentC providers
     ComponentB (parent)
          │
          ↑ not in ComponentB providers
     Root Injector
          │
          ✓ found! Returns the root singleton
```

## Component-Level Providers — Scoped Instances

```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'app-cart',
  providers: [CartService]  // NEW CartService instance per cart component
})
export class CartComponent {
  constructor(private cart: CartService) {}
}
```

```
Two CartComponents on the same page get SEPARATE CartService instances:

<app-cart>  ← CartService instance A
<app-cart>  ← CartService instance B (different!)

This is useful for:
  - Wizard steps (each step owns its own state service)
  - Popup/dialog with isolated state
  - Re-usable forms with separate form state
```

## Injecting Services

```typescript
// Method 1: Constructor injection (classic)
@Component({ ... })
export class ProfileComponent {
  constructor(
    private userService: UserService,
    private authService: AuthService
  ) {}
}

// Method 2: inject() function (Angular 14+ — works anywhere, even outside constructor)
import { inject } from '@angular/core';

@Component({ ... })
export class ProfileComponent {
  private userService = inject(UserService);
  private authService = inject(AuthService);
}
```

`inject()` is more powerful — it works in standalone functions, factory providers, and signals setup.

## Injection Tokens — When There's No Class to Inject

```typescript
import { InjectionToken } from '@angular/core';

// Define a token for a config object
export const APP_CONFIG = new InjectionToken<AppConfig>('app.config');

// Provide it in root or component:
@NgModule({
  providers: [
    { provide: APP_CONFIG, useValue: { apiUrl: 'https://api.example.com', debug: false } }
  ]
})

// Inject it:
export class ApiService {
  private config = inject(APP_CONFIG);
  // config.apiUrl is available
}
```

## Provider Recipes

```typescript
providers: [
  // useClass — provide a different implementation:
  { provide: UserService, useClass: MockUserService },  // useful for testing

  // useValue — provide a constant:
  { provide: API_URL, useValue: 'https://prod.api.com' },

  // useFactory — compute the value:
  {
    provide: LogLevel,
    useFactory: () => environment.production ? 'error' : 'debug'
  },

  // useExisting — alias one token to another:
  { provide: LegacyService, useExisting: NewService }
]
```

## @Optional, @Self, @SkipSelf, @Host

```typescript
class MyComponent {
  constructor(
    @Optional() private cache?: CacheService,  // don't error if not provided
    @Self() private myService: MyService,       // only look in this component's injector
    @SkipSelf() private parent: ParentService,  // skip this, look in parent injector
    @Host() private host: HostService           // only look up to host element
  ) {}
}
```

## Common Pitfalls
- **Multiple instances when expecting a singleton** — if you add a service to both `providers: []` in a module AND in a component, the component gets its own instance, not the root singleton.
- **`new MyService()` in tests** — don't. Use Angular's TestBed to inject so DI works correctly.
- **Circular dependencies** — ServiceA injecting ServiceB that injects ServiceA. Extract shared logic into a third service.
- **providedIn: 'root' but the test can't override it** — in tests, override with `{ provide: UserService, useClass: MockUserService }` in TestBed providers.
- **forget to import HttpClientModule** — if a service uses HttpClient, the consuming module needs `HttpClientModule` (or `provideHttpClient()` in standalone apps).

## Connections
- **angular-rxjs** — services typically return Observables; components subscribe to them
- **angular-forms** — FormBuilder is an injectable service
- **angular-routing** — Router and ActivatedRoute are injectable services

